91
00:07:15,440 --> 00:07:24,280
poets of this tradition were Mir Muhammad Thape Mir 1722 to 1810 and Mirza Asadul al-Achan

92
00:07:24,280 --> 00:07:29,720
Ralib 1797 to 1869.

93
00:07:29,720 --> 00:07:33,660
Formally speaking a guzzle is a set of two line verses.

94
00:07:33,660 --> 00:07:38,040
They aren't technically couplets since in most of them the two lines don't rhyme and

95
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:41,480
in a couplet usually the two lines rhyme.

96
00:07:41,480 --> 00:07:46,760
Ideally there are to be an odd number of them and ideally the number is to be something

97
00:07:46,760 --> 00:07:49,680
like seven or nine.

98
00:07:49,680 --> 00:07:53,200
Could we make the sound louder would that help would that make it easier sir?

99
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:54,200
Is it okay?

100
00:07:54,200 --> 00:07:55,200
Okay.

101
00:07:55,200 --> 00:08:03,360
They these verses share a strictly defined Arabic derived quantitative meter and at the

102
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:09,920
end of each verse they also share a common rhyme syllable and after it usually a common

103
00:08:09,920 --> 00:08:14,280
repeated refrain word or words as well.

104
00:08:14,280 --> 00:08:20,320
Beyond this the verses of a guzzle share only the larger guzzle universe of stylized

105
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:23,840
characters scenes actions and images.

106
00:08:23,840 --> 00:08:30,520
A guzzle in short is a series of semantically independent two line mini poems that have

107
00:08:30,520 --> 00:08:36,280
a strong formal unity but usually no particular unity beyond that.

108
00:08:36,280 --> 00:08:43,200
Thus in performance oral recidors and singers freely rearrange the verses of a guzzle and

109
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:47,280
almost always omit a good number of them.

110
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:53,080
The first verse of a guzzle commonly incorporates the rhyme and refrain at the end of both lines

111
00:08:53,080 --> 00:08:56,120
instead of only at the end of the second line.

112
00:08:56,120 --> 00:09:00,440
If it does this it's called an opening verse there's a special name for it matla.

